\begin_layout Standard
The main point of using a DSL is to separate the description of computations
 from the process of their evaluation.
 One creates a 
\series bold
DSL program
\series default

\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
DSL program
\end_layout

\end_inset

 as a data structure that fully describes what computations and side effects
 need to be run but does not actually perform any of those computations
 or side-effects.
 Helper functions are implemented for creating the DSL program values, for
 combining several DSL programs into larger ones, and for interpreting (or
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

running
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) DSL programs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This design pattern is known as an 
\series bold
embedded
\series default
 
\series bold
DSL
\series default

\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
embedded DSL
\end_layout

\end_inset

, meaning that it is implemented not as a separate new language but as a
 library in an existing programming language (e.g., Scala).
 This chapter only considers embedded DSLs and calls them just 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

DSL
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

s for brevity.
\end_layout

