\begin_layout Subsection
Expressing existential quantifiers via universal quantifiers
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will now motivate and define the connection between existential and universal
 quantifiers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The previous section shows that a type expression with an existentially
 quantified type, such as 
\begin_inset Formula $\exists C.\,A\times C\times\left(C\rightarrow B\right)$
\end_inset

, hides the actual type under the parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 and only exposes its existence.
 Fully parametric
\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
fully parametric!code
\end_layout

\end_inset

 external code may work with values of type 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 as long as 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is treated as an unknown and arbitrary type.
 This agrees with the restriction that fully parametric code may not make
 decisions based on the actual type assigned to a type parameter.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us formulate this property in more precise terms.
 An example of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

external code
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is the function 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

toInt
\end_layout

\end_inset

 shown in the previous section.
 The type signature and the code of 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

toInt
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is written in the short notation as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{toInt}:\left(\exists C.\,\text{Int}\times C\times(C\rightarrow\text{Int})\right)\rightarrow\text{Int}\quad,\quad\quad\text{toInt}\triangleq(\exists C.\,a^{:\text{Int}}\times c^{:C}\times p^{:C\rightarrow\text{Int}})\rightarrow a+p(c)\quad.
\]

\end_inset

Generalizing from this example, we say that 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

code external to the existential quantifier
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 means any function having an argument of an existentially quantified type.
 For instance, this could be a function of type 
\begin_inset Formula $(\exists C.\,F^{C})\rightarrow D$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $F^{C}$
\end_inset

 is any type expression and 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 is any type.
 The existential quantifier allows us to use values of the type 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 as long as the code does not depend on a specific type that is hidden under
 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

.
 This means treating 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 as a 
\emph on
type parameter
\emph default
.
 Functions with type parameters have type signatures with the 
\emph on
universal
\emph default
 quantifier, such as 
\begin_inset Formula $\forall C.\:F^{C}\rightarrow G^{C}$
\end_inset

, showing that the same code works with any type 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

.
 So, we a fully parametric function of type 
\begin_inset Formula $(\exists C.\,F^{C})\rightarrow D$
\end_inset

 must be a function of type 
\begin_inset Formula $F^{C}\rightarrow D$
\end_inset

 that works in the same way for all types 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

.
 We usually write the types of such functions as 
\begin_inset Formula $\forall C.\,F^{C}\rightarrow D$
\end_inset

.
 We conclude that the following types are equivalent:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\text{for any fixed type }D:\quad(\exists C.\,F^{C})\rightarrow D\cong\forall C.\,(F^{C}\rightarrow D)\quad.\label{eq:existential-via-universal}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is important that the universal quantifier in 
\begin_inset Formula $\forall C.\,F^{C}\rightarrow D$
\end_inset

 is 
\emph on
outside
\emph default
 the entire type expression 
\begin_inset Formula $F^{C}\rightarrow D$
\end_inset

.
 (The type notations 
\begin_inset Formula $\forall C.\,(F^{C}\rightarrow D)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\forall C.\,F^{C}\rightarrow D$
\end_inset

 are equivalent.) In contrast, the type 
\begin_inset Formula $(\exists C.\,F^{C})\rightarrow D$
\end_inset

 contains the existential quantifier (
\begin_inset Formula $\exists C$
\end_inset

) 
\emph on
inside
\emph default
 a function argument.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To illustrate the type equivalence
