\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A value of an existentially quantified type, such as 
\begin_inset Formula $\exists C.\,F^{C}$
\end_inset

, must be created by using a specific type for 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

.
 So, we may view the type 
\begin_inset Formula $\exists C.\,F^{C}$
\end_inset

 as an 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

infinite disjunction
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 ranging over all possible types that could have been used for 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\exists C.\,F^{C}=F^{\text{Int}}+F^{\text{String}}+F^{\text{List}^{\text{Int}}}+...
\]

\end_inset

Now look at the following type equivalence where a disjunctive type is in
 the function argument:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(A+B\right)\rightarrow D\cong\left(A\rightarrow D\right)\times\left(B\rightarrow D\right)\quad.
\]

\end_inset

Write the same type equivalence using the infinite product and the infinite
 disjunction:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(F^{\text{Int}}+F^{\text{String}}+F^{\text{List}^{\text{Int}}}+...)\rightarrow D\cong(F^{\text{Int}}\rightarrow D)\times(F^{\text{String}}\rightarrow D)\times(F^{\text{List}^{\text{Int}}}\rightarrow D)\times...
\]

\end_inset

This (non-rigorous) formula can be rewritten in terms of type quantifiers
 as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\exists C.\,F^{C})\rightarrow D\cong\forall C.\,(F^{C}\rightarrow D)\quad.
\]

\end_inset

This is the same as Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:existential-via-universal"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another way to see why Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:existential-via-universal"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) works is to view the case class constructor 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

L1[A, B, C]()
\end_layout

\end_inset

 as a function from a triple of type 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(A, C, C => B)
\end_layout

\end_inset

 to a value of type 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

L[A, B]
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 For clarity, let us denote that function temporary by 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

f
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and write:
\begin_inset listings
inline false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

def f[A, B, C](a: A, c: C, p: C => B): L[A, B] = L1(a, c, p) 
\end_layout

\end_inset

This code is just a function with some type parameters; that is, a function
 that works in the same way for all types.
 So, the type notation for the function 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

f
\end_layout

\end_inset

 must be written via the 
\emph on
universal
\emph default
 quantifiers for each type parameter:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f:\forall(A,B,C).\,A\times C\times(C\rightarrow B)\rightarrow L^{A,B}\quad.
\]

\end_inset

The equivalent notation with the existential quantifier for 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 looks like this:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f:\forall(A,B).\,\big(\exists C.\,A\times C\times(C\rightarrow B)\big)\rightarrow L^{A,B}=\forall(A,B).\,\big(\exists C.\,\text{L1}^{A,B,C})\rightarrow L^{A,B}\quad.
\]

\end_inset

This explains why the existential quantifier is represented in Scala by
 a case class with an extra type parameter, such as 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

L1[A, B, C]
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 The type parameter 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

C
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is existentially quantified because it does not appear in 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

L[A, B]
\end_layout

\end_inset

, while the two other parameters (
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

A
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

B
\end_layout

\end_inset

) do appear in 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

L[A, B]
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and are therefore universally quantified.
\end_layout

