\begin_layout Standard
Usually, typeclasses impose some laws on their methods.
 We will now develop a rigorous description of 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

-typeclass laws where all laws are represented by values of a certain type.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For motivation, look at the laws for a monoid type 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\text{left identity law}:\quad & \text{for all }x^{:A}\quad:\quad e_{_{A}}\oplus_{_{A}}x=x\quad,\\
\text{right identity law}:\quad & \text{for all }x^{:A}\quad:\quad x\oplus_{_{A}}e_{_{A}}=x\quad,\\
\text{associativity law}:\quad & \text{for all }x^{:A},y^{:A},z^{:A}\quad:\quad(x\oplus_{_{A}}y)\oplus_{_{A}}z=x\oplus_{_{A}}(y\oplus_{_{A}}z)\quad,\\
\text{commutativity law}:\quad & \text{for all }x^{:A},y^{:A}\quad:\quad x\oplus_{_{A}}y=y\oplus_{_{A}}x\quad.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Each law is an equation between some expressions of the same type 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 These expressions are computed via the monoid's operations using arbitrary
 values (
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

), which are also of type 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 To generalize this situation, we write the monoid laws as equations of
 the form 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}(...)=f_{2}(...)$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{for all }x^{:A},y^{:A},z^{:A}\quad:\quad f_{1}(\oplus_{_{A}},e_{_{A}},x,y,z)=f_{2}(\oplus_{_{A}},e_{_{A}},x,y,z)\quad.
\]

\end_inset

For the associativity law, we need to choose the functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{2}$
\end_inset

 as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\text{for the associativity law}:\quad & f_{1}(\oplus,e,x,y,z)\triangleq(x\oplus y)\oplus z\quad,\quad\quad f_{2}(\oplus,e,x,y,z)\triangleq x\oplus(y\oplus z)\quad.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

The functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{2}$
\end_inset

 for the identity laws do not depend on 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

, for instance:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\text{for the left identity law}:\quad & f_{1}(\oplus,e,x,y,z)\triangleq e\oplus x\quad,\quad\quad f_{2}(\oplus,e,x,y,z)\triangleq x\quad.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

The functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{2}$
\end_inset

 for the commutativity law will not depend on 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The data in the pair 
\begin_inset Formula $(\oplus_{_{A}},e_{_{A}})$
\end_inset

 is a value of type 
\begin_inset Formula $P^{A}\rightarrow A$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $P^{A}\triangleq\bbnum 1+A\times A$
\end_inset

 for the 
\begin_inset listings
inline true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Monoid
\end_layout

\end_inset

 typeclass (but 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 will be different for other typeclasses).
 So, the functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{2}$
\end_inset

 have type 
\begin_inset Formula $(P^{A}\rightarrow A)\times A\times A\times A\rightarrow A$
\end_inset

.
 The pair 
\begin_inset Formula $(f_{1},f_{2})$
\end_inset

 is equivalent to a single value of type 
\begin_inset Formula $(P^{A}\rightarrow A)\times A\times A\times A\rightarrow A\times A$
\end_inset

.
 Each law corresponds to a specific value of that type, which we will call
 a 
\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
law function
\end_layout

\end_inset


\series bold
law function
\series default
.
