\begin_layout Subsection
Universally quantified function types cover all other types
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It turns out that all fully parametric type expressions are equivalent to
 some type expressions that use only two type constructions: the function
 type (
\begin_inset Formula $A\rightarrow B$
\end_inset

) and the universal quantifier (
\begin_inset Formula $\forall A.\,F^{A}$
\end_inset

).
 If a programming language only supports these two type constructions, one
 can write a library that implements all other type constructions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will now show the required type expressions and prove their equivalence.
 The main tools in those proofs are the Church encoding and the Yoneda lemma.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Void type
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The void type (
\begin_inset Formula $\bbnum 0$
\end_inset

) is equivalent to the type expression 
\begin_inset Formula $\forall A.\,A$
\end_inset

.
 To prove that 
\begin_inset Formula $\forall A.\,A\cong\bbnum 0$
\end_inset

, we may use the Yoneda lemma:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\forall A.\,A\cong\forall A.\,\bbnum 1\rightarrow A\cong\forall A.\,(\bbnum 0\rightarrow A)\rightarrow A\cong\bbnum 0\quad.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Unit type
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The unit type (
\begin_inset Formula $\bbnum 1$
\end_inset

) is equivalent to 
\begin_inset Formula $\forall A.\,A\rightarrow A$
\end_inset

.
 To prove that, we may use the Yoneda lemma:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\forall A.\,A\rightarrow A\cong\forall A.\,(\bbnum 1\rightarrow A)\rightarrow A\cong\bbnum 1\quad.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Products
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The type 
\begin_inset Formula $A\times B$
\end_inset

 is equivalent to 
\begin_inset Formula $\forall T.\,(A\rightarrow B\rightarrow T)\rightarrow T$
\end_inset

.
 To prove that, we use uncurrying and the Yoneda lemma:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\forall T.\,(A\rightarrow B\rightarrow T)\rightarrow T\cong\forall T.\,(A\times B\rightarrow T)\rightarrow T\cong A\times B\quad.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Co-products
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The type 
\begin_inset Formula $A+B$
\end_inset

 is equivalent to 
\begin_inset Formula $\forall T.\,(A\rightarrow T)\rightarrow(B\rightarrow T)\rightarrow T$
\end_inset

.
 To prove that, we use the Yoneda lemma:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
 & \forall T.\,(A\rightarrow T)\rightarrow(B\rightarrow T)\rightarrow T\cong\forall T.\,(A\rightarrow T)\times(B\rightarrow T)\rightarrow T\\
 & \quad\cong\forall T.\,(A+B\rightarrow T)\rightarrow T\cong A+B\quad.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Recursive types
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A recursive type 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 defined via the type equation 
\begin_inset Formula $T\triangleq F^{T}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is a covariant functor, is equivalent to the Church encoding of 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
T\cong\forall A.\,(F^{A}\rightarrow A)\rightarrow A\quad.
\]

\end_inset

This is proved in Statement
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


